summary:
I have successfully identified and fixed the "needle" (bug) in the container.

## Problem Analysis

The issue was in the `fileproc` application located in `/app/src/main.rs`. The bug was in the `process_file` function which used a fixed 64KB buffer to read input files. This caused silent data truncation when processing files larger than 64KB.

## Root Cause

The original code had this problematic section:
```rust
const BUFFER_SIZE: usize = 65536; // 64KB

fn process_file(input_path: &str, output_path: &str) -> io::Result<()> {
    let mut file = fs::File::open(input_path)?;
    let mut buffer = [0u8; BUFFER_SIZE];

    // Read file into fixed buffer — silently truncates if file > 64KB
    let bytes_read = file.read(&mut buffer)?;

    let data = &buffer[..bytes_read];
    // ... process data
}
```

This would only read up to 64KB regardless of the file size, causing data loss for larger files.

## Fix Applied

I modified `/app/src/main.rs` to read the entire file content instead:
```rust
fn process_file(input_path: &str, output_path: &str) -> io::Result<()> {
    let mut file = fs::File::open(input_path)?;
    let mut data = Vec::new();

    // Read entire file content
    file.read_to_end(&mut data)?;

    let transformed = transform::process(&data);
    // ... rest unchanged
}
```

## Verification

The fix has been tested and verified:
1. Created a 100KB test file (larger than the 64KB buffer)
2. Before fix: Output was truncated to 65536 bytes
3. After fix: Output correctly matches input size of 102400 bytes
4. The test script now passes completely

The "needle" has been found and removed - the file processing now correctly handles files of any size without silent data corruption.
